============================================================
EFFECTIVE FRIEDMANN EQUATIONS WITH EXPANSION-HISTORY ACTIVATION
============================================================

1. Standard Friedmann background
------------------------------------------------------------

For a spatially flat FRW universe the Friedmann equation is

    H² = (8πG/3) (ρ_m + ρ_Λ)

with

    ρ_m ∝ a⁻³
    ρ_Λ = constant.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. Activated matter sector
------------------------------------------------------------

In the curvature–memory framework the gravitational contribution
of the matter sector is modulated by an activation fraction

    g(z) ∈ [0,1].

The effective matter density becomes

    ρ_m^eff(z) = g(z) ρ_m(z).

Thus

    ρ_m^eff = g(z) ρ_m0 (1+z)³.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Modified Friedmann equation
------------------------------------------------------------

Substituting the activated matter density gives

    H²(z) =
        (8πG/3)
        [ g(z) ρ_m0 (1+z)³ + ρ_Λ ].

Writing in terms of density parameters

    Ω_m = ρ_m0 / ρ_crit
    Ω_Λ = ρ_Λ / ρ_crit

yields

    H²(z) =
        H₀² [ Ω_m (1+z)³ g(z) + Ω_Λ ].


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Activation law
------------------------------------------------------------

From the geometric derivation

    U(z) = ln(1+z).

The activated fraction is

    g(z) = 1 − exp[ − (U(z)/u_s)^ν ].

Therefore

    g(z) =
        1 − exp[ − ( ln(1+z) / u_s )^ν ].


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Equality-normalised scale
------------------------------------------------------------

If the activation scale is tied to matter–Λ equality,

    u_s = α u_eq

with

    u_eq = (1/3) ln((1−Ω_m)/Ω_m),

then

    g(z) =
        1 − exp[
            − ( ln(1+z) / (α u_eq) )^ν
          ].


------------------------------------------------------------
6. Limiting behaviour
------------------------------------------------------------

Early universe (z ≫ 1):

    ln(1+z) → large
    g(z) → 1

so

    H² ≈ H₀² [ Ω_m (1+z)³ + Ω_Λ ]

recovering the standard matter-dominated behaviour.


Present epoch (z → 0):

    ln(1+z) → 0
    g(z) → 0

so the effective matter contribution is suppressed.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. Effective dark-energy interpretation
------------------------------------------------------------

The Friedmann equation can be written in standard form

    H² = H₀² [ Ω_m (1+z)³ + ρ_DE^eff(z) ].

where

    ρ_DE^eff(z) =
        Ω_Λ − Ω_m (1+z)³ [1 − g(z)].

Thus the activation mechanism produces an evolving
effective dark-energy density.


------------------------------------------------------------
8. Equation of state
------------------------------------------------------------

The effective equation of state is

    w_eff(z)
      = −1
        + (1+z)/(3 ρ_DE^eff)
          dρ_DE^eff/dz.

Because g(z) evolves smoothly with redshift,
the model produces a time-dependent dark-energy behaviour.


------------------------------------------------------------
9. Summary
------------------------------------------------------------

The activated Friedmann equation is

    H²(z) =
        H₀² [
            Ω_m (1+z)³
            (1 − exp[−( ln(1+z) / u_s )^ν])
            + Ω_Λ
        ].

This equation contains only two activation parameters:

    u_s  (activation scale)
    ν    (threshold distribution shape).

The cosmological dynamics therefore follow directly from the
geometric activation law derived from integrated expansion history.
